We are going to create a new column that is the hydologic year, or the precipitation year that the tree growth seems to correspond to. In the previous lab we looked at correlations between tree ring width and monthly precipitation. It seemed that tree ring width is most correlated with precipitation from the previous July to the current June.

To create the hydrologic year, we will shift the year column forward by 6 months, so that the new year starts in July rather than next January. Well use the lead function in the dplyr package.

precip.df <- precip.df %>% mutate(water_year = lead(year, 6))
head(precip.df, 20)

With this water_year column in place, we want to calculate the total precipitation each water_year. This is a group and summarize task.

annual_precip <- precip.df %>% group_by(water_year) %>% 
  summarize(precip=sum(precip)) %>%
  filter(water_year>1895)
# Don't forget to filter out year=1895 because it wasn't complete.
head(annual_precip)

rwi.precip.df <- left_join(rwi, annual_precip, by=c('year'='water_year'))

Exploratory analysis

Plot a scatterplot. You should always visualize the data first.

ggplot(data=rwi.precip.df) + geom_point(aes(x=precip, y=rwi))
## Warning: Removed 2032 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

There is clearly a positive relationship between annual precipitation and ring width. There is a possibility of nonlinear relationship; it appears that there are diminishing returns to precipitation. A little precipitation is good for trees, but eventually an increase in rain does not lead to any extra increase in tree growth.

Linear regression

Nonetheless, well fit a linear regression to the data.

# Fit the model
model <- lm(rwi~precip, data=rwi.precip.df)
# Print out a summary
summary(model)

We see that each increase in the ring width corresponds to a 0.1085 in increase in annual precipitation. If we wanted to create 95% confidence intervals, we would have 0.1085 plus/minus 2 times 0.0097, or [0.0988, 0.1181]. This interval does not include zero. Thus, a slope of zero (no relationship between precipitation and ring width) is not consistent with the data. Admittedly, this isnt that interesting. We could have speculated that a zero slope was not consistent with the data just by looking at the scatterplot.

We also see the \(R^2\) of 0.5397.

Regression Diagnostics

Regression is easy enough. We can always run a regression and get results. But should we? Should we run the regression? Should we trust the results? For this, we need to qualitatively evaluate the assumptions. This is mixture of knowing your data, knowing your science, looking at a few different types of plots, and a little creativity. Whats worse, is that its a lot of work, and its never going to get published. It is just assumed that the regression is OK, and if a reviewer questions you on the regression, you should have the supporting evidence that you will need already.

Here is a quick way to do the regression diagnostic plots.

plot(model) # You can then step through each plot, Hit <Return> to see the next plot

# Or you can see one plot at a time, e.g.
plot(model, which=2)

First, a little about residuals. First of all, regression residuals are not population model errors. The residuals are #estimates# of the population errors. Not all regression residuals are created equal. Some data rows have residuals that are noisier than other rows. Even if the data have constant variance, the regression residuals do not. The standardized residuals correct for this. There is also something called studentized residuals. There is usually very little difference in practice, but the studentized residuals may be more robust to outliers.

Homework: For the first three plots, describe wich assumptions they help to visually evaluate.

There appears to be a slight nonlinearity in the dataset. As you move from low to high fitted values, the residuals tend to be low, then high, then low again. Its hard to tell how much of a problem this is, and how to fix it. Possible technical solutions might be:

  1. log or square root transforming the predictand and/or predictor variables. Transforming the dependent variable is not a problem for the regression, but it does complicate how we interpret the prediction..
  2. Adding ring width squared (this is a multivariate regression, will cover that in class soon)
  3. Nonlinear regression (I wont cover this in lab)

If you want to create your own plot of residuals, you can calculate the residuals, rstandard, and rstudent functions to add the residuals to your data.frame.
